data(multishapes)

# our old friend the iris dataset
data(iris)
x <- as.matrix(iris[,1:4])

db <- dbscan(x, eps = .4, minPts = 4)
db

# Visualize results (noise is shown in black)
pairs(x, col = db$cluster + 1L)

opt <- optics(x, eps = 1, minPts = 4)

# Extract DBSCAN-like clustering from OPTICS and create a reachability

opt <- extractDBSCAN(opt, eps_cl = .4)

# Run HDBSCAN (captures stable clusters)

hdb

# Visualize the results as a simplified tree
plot(hdb, show_flat = T)

# See how well each point corresponds to the clusters found by the model used
colors <- mapply(function(col, i) adjustcolor(col, alpha.f = hdb$membership_prob[i]), 
                 palette()[hdb$cluster+1], seq_along(hdb$cluster))
plot(x, col=colors, pch=20)

## find suitable eps parameter using a k-NN plot for k = dim + 1
## Look for the knee!
kNNdistplot(iris[1:4], k = 5)
##kNNdistplot(as.matrix(iris[1:4]), k = 5)

res

pairs(iris, col = res$cluster + 1L)

## use precomputed frNN
fr <- frNN(iris[1:4], eps = .5)
dbscan(fr, minPts = 5)

set.seed(1234)
# fpc package
res.fpc <- fpc::dbscan(iris, eps = 0.4, MinPts = 4)
# dbscan package
res.db <- dbscan::dbscan(iris, 0.4, 4)
fviz_cluster(res.fpc, iris, geom = "point")
fviz_cluster(res.db, iris, geom = "point")

data(moons)
plot(moons, pch=20)

# run the hierarchial version of dbscan on "moons" data
cl <- hdbscan(moons, minPts = 5)
cl

# what does hdbscan make of it?
plot(moons, col=cl$cluster+1, pch=20)  # add offset of +1 to account for any outliers

In[13]:
####################################################################

df <- multishapes[, 1:2]  # just the data and not the  class labels

# Compute DBSCAN using fpc package
set.seed(123)
db_fpc <- fpc::dbscan(df, eps = 0.15, MinPts = 5)
db_fpc
# Plot DBSCAN results
plot(db_fpc, df, main = "DBSCAN", frame = FALSE)

# Compute using dbscan::
db_scan <- dbscan::dbscan(df, 0.4, 4)
db_scan
plot(db_scan, df, main = "DBSCAN", frame = FALSE)
